{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471739"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:51:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:51:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"654"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17577217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17577217"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T03:39:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T03:39:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"654"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582705"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:52:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:52:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"654"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/654"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.09,0.71,0.07,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"654"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49360"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/654"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"654"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34610"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2147"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13615"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49360"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a long history of recurrent chest and sinus infections and a chronic cough. She has a medical history of allergic rhinitis. Her family are recent migrants from Iran. She does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. Her weight and height are at the 5th percentiles. Nasal examination shows bilateral nasal polyps. Chest auscultation reveals reduced breath sounds bilaterally and wheezes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary function test","CT chest and sinuses","Chloride sweat test","Full blood count and immunoglobulin estimation","Echocardiogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms are consistent with cystic fibrosis (CF), for which the \u003Cstrong\u003Echloride sweat test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation. CF is an autosomal recessive disorder characterised by abnormal chloride channels in the cells of the exocrine glands. This leads to hyperviscous secretions that can block the lumen of the channels connected to these exocrine glands. CF presents with a wide range of symptoms involving the gastrointestinal system (e.g., meconium ileus, pancreatitis leading to malabsorption, biliary cirrhosis, CF-related diabetes), respiratory system (e.g., chronic sinusitis, nasal polyps, obstructive airway disease with bronchiectasis), and urogenital system (e.g., infertility). Impaired ciliary clearance of hyperviscous respiratory secretions predisposes these patients to recurrent respiratory infections leading to bronchiectasis. Malabsorption due to pancreatic insufficiency can present with low weight and height percentiles, and these patients are particularly at an increased risk of vitamin deficiencies. Due to defective chloride channels, the sweat glands of these patients secrete particularly salty sweat. A chloride concentration of \u226560 mEq/L in chloride sweat test is consistent with the diagnosis of CF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest and sinuses\u003C/strong\u003E would reveal signs of bronchiectasis (e.g., dilated airways) and sinusitis (e.g., air-fluid levels, soft tissue inflammation). However, CT scan is not diagnostic of CF itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFull blood count and immunoglobulin estimation\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful in congenital immunodeficiency disorders (e.g., Bruton agammaglobulinaemia, selective IgA deficiency). Although this patient\u0027s long history of recurrent sinopulmonary infections is also seen in agammaglobulinaemia, the presence of nasal polyps and wheezes, typical of obstructive airway disease, are more likely to be seen in CF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary function test\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to assess the extent of lung involvement in cystic fibrosis; however, it is not the diagnostic tool for CF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used in the initial diagnosis of CF. While CF can lead to cardiac complications such as cor pulmonale in advanced stages, there are no specific cardiac findings that would diagnose CF. An echocardiogram might be considered later in the disease course to assess for pulmonary hypertension or right heart strain, but it is not the appropriate first-line diagnostic test for suspected CF.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The chloride sweat test is the standard investigation for the diagnosis of cystic fibrosis."],"references":["Farrell PM, White TB, Ren CL, Hempstead SE, Accurso F, Derichs N, Howenstine M, McColley SA, Rock M, Rosenfeld M, Sermet-Gaudelus I, Southern KW, Marshall BC, Sosnay PR. Diagnosis of Cystic Fibrosis: Consensus Guidelines from the Cystic Fibrosis Foundation. J Pediatr. 2017 Feb;181S:S4-S15.e1.","Yu E, Sharma S. Cystic Fibrosis. [Updated 2020 Aug 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK493206/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34610"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"654"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34610"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-28T16:15:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-28T16:15:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"654"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49360"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"ite